2.2. Procedure
All participants underwent an MRI scan (in a separate session)
to provide anatomical anchors for localization of MEG data. MEG
was recorded as participants performed a three-tone oddball task
requiring the identiﬁcation of infrequent target tones (15%,
1000 Hz, 300 ms) embedded in a series of standard tones (70%,
900 Hz, 300 ms) and infrequent threat related distractors (15%, a
very unpleasant sound of shattering glass (800 ms), adapted from
Levy et al. (2003). There were 330 stimuli presentations: 50 targets
(‘oddball’), 50 distractors (‘novel’) and 230 standard tones (‘stan-
dard’). Tones were presented through headphones in a random
order. Interstimulus intervals (ISI) ranged randomly from 900 to
1000 ms in order to eliminate anticipation bias. Participants were
instructed to press a button with their right index ﬁnger every time
a target tone occurred and not to press the button in response to
the standard or the distracting stimuli. Prior to the task, every par-
ticipant completed a practice block until correctly identifying the
target stimuli while ignoring all other stimuli. Reaction times for
the target stimuli were computed on trials in which the participant
answered correctly within 1300 ms post stimulus. Omission errors
included any missed target tones or response with latency greater
than 1300 ms following the onset of the target stimulus. Commis-
sion errors included any incorrect response following the distract-
ing or standard stimuli within 1300 ms of stimulus onset. See
Supplementary Methods in Supplementary Information for addi-
tional details regarding the MEG methods.
2.3. MEG analysis
Data was time-locked and segmented into 900 ms epochs start-
ing 200 ms before stimulus presentation. Epochs were baseline
corrected to the pre-stimulus period in each sensor and averaged
to yield the event-related ﬁelds in each condition. In order to avoid
a confound of number of trials in the various conditions, for each
subject, the number of trials in the smallest condition was deter-
mined and the same number of trials were drawn randomly from
the other conditions. The average number of trials analyzed across
subjects was 42.9.
Sources were localized with synthetic aperture magnetometry
(SAM) beamforming analysis (Robinson and Vrba, 1999), resulting
in ‘‘virtual sensor” time-series for every condition (see Supplemen-
tary Methods in Supplementary Information for description of SAM
analysis).
Voxel-level group statistics, for each component, was con-
ducted using AFNI (Cox, 1996). Differential activation for target
vs. standard stimuli, and distractor vs. standard stimuli in the
two groups was tested using mixed ANOVAs (group X stimulus)
for each time-window of interest. Dividing the conditions into
two separate tests enabled a better understanding of the sources
for each of the infrequent tones (i.e. targets and distractors) in
comparison to the standard condition which was treated as the
baseline. In order to control for multiple comparisons, a Monte
Carlo simulation implemented by AFNI AlphaSim was used to cal-
culate the probability of a false positive, according to which the
minimal cluster size with p < 0.05 was one cubic cm (8 voxels).
Here we used a cluster threshold of p < 0.01 for that cluster size.
The mean activity across voxels in signiﬁcant clusters was used
in further contrasts using the Bonferroni correction. To further val-
idate our results, a non-parametric permutation (Monte Carlo) test
was conducted for clusters in which a signiﬁcant interaction
between group X stimulus was found (Nichols and Holmes,
2002; Singh et al., 2003) (see Supplementary Methods in Supple-
mentary Information for description of the permutation test).
To evaluate the relationship between P3 impairment and clinical
severity, correlations between CAPS scores and mean cluster activ-
ity of each participant were assessed using Pearson correlations.
CAPS scores were divided into three distinct scores according to
the DSM-IV symptom clusters; re-experiencing, avoidance and
hyper-arousal. An analysis of partial correlation between each of
these symptom cluster scores and mean activity in each of the brain
clusters was computed, controlling for depression and anxiety.
3. Results
3.1. Descriptive measures
Demographic information and psychological interview results
can be found in Table 1. The control and PTSD groups did not differ
on age [t(28) = 1.03, n.s] or time since the occurrence of the trauma
[t(28) = 1.35, n.s]. PTSD symptoms score of PTSD patients were in
the severe range while control participants were not symptomatic.
Clinical ratings showed, as anticipated, that PTSD patients had
signiﬁcantly
higher
PTSD
[t(15) = 12.54,
p < .001],
depression
[t(15) = 6, p < .001] and anxiety symptoms [t(15) = 9.25, p < .001]
compared with controls.
Twelve of ﬁfteen PTSD patients (80%) were taking psychotropic
medications at the time of study. About 80% (10/12) were receiving
antidepressants for either depression or anxiety symptoms and
42% (5/12) were receiving antipsychotics as major tranquilizers
or for antidepressant augmentation. Two patients (17%) were
receiving mood stabilizers for impulse control and hypervigilance
symptoms. A third were taking hypnotics or benzodiazepines for
sleep disturbance and anxiety symptoms. None of the control par-
ticipants met criteria for any psychiatric disorder and were not tak-
ing any psychotropic medication.
3.2. Behavioral data
Mean reaction times for the target tones did not differ between
PTSD (mean 579 ms, SD = 0.13) and control group (mean 578 ms,
SD = 0.09). PTSD patients had more incorrect responses to standard
stimuli (mean 3.73, SD = 7.75) compared with controls (mean 0.64,
