SD = 0.97) [t(28) = 2.04, p < .05]. Differences between the groups
for percentage of correct hits (PTSD mean 83%, SD = 17.59; controls
mean 90%, SD = 14.69) and incorrect responses to distractors (PTSD
mean 7.01, SD = 12.15; controls mean 4.45, SD = 6.69) did not
reach signiﬁcance, although a trend toward patients exhibiting
more response errors was evident.
3.3. MEG results
Both rare stimuli (distractors and targets) showed increased
amplitude relative to standards tones across groups in two time
windows at approximately 170–270 ms and 300–400 ms post
stimulus, which roughly correspond to the novelty P3 and the
P3b components (Fig. 1). Increased amplitude in both time win-
dows corresponds with previous ﬁndings, indicating that all devi-
ant stimuli elicit the Novelty P3 as well as the P300 (Spencer
et al., 1999). SAM beamforming source estimates were conducted
separately at each time window.
Target & distractor processing: Although our main focus is on the
difference between groups, we ﬁrst examined the brain activity eli-
cited by targets and distractors in both PTSD and healthy controls.
Brieﬂy, across groups brain activation in response to the distractors
in the ﬁrst time window was most prominent in the medial frontal
gyrus, the anterior and posterior cingulate and the superior tempo-
ral gyrus, whereas activity in response to the target stimuli in the
second time window was most prominent in the ACC, dlPFC and
the inferior parietal lobule (IPL). These ﬁndings are similar to pre-
vious published data (Huang et al., 2005; Volpe et al., 2007) (For a
full report see Supplementary Results and Table S1 in Supplemen-
tary Information).
3.3.1. Group differences for the target stimuli
In the ﬁrst time window (170–270 ms), the mixed ANOVA
(group X stimulus type) demonstrated a signiﬁcant main effect
for group (across stimulus type), with higher activation of PTSD
patients relative to controls in the right medial frontal gyrus
(F(1,28) = 15.343, p < .001) and in a cluster encompassing areas
between the right precuneus and the superior parietal lobule
(F(1,28) = 18.609,
p < 0.001).
In
the
second
time
window
(300–400 ms), PTSD patients had higher activation bilaterally in
the cingulate cortex (F(1,28) = 15.041, p < .001) and in the left
middle occipital gyrus (F(1,28) = 12.215, p < .01).
In both time windows, the differential pattern of activity in
response to target and standard tones varied signiﬁcantly between
PTSD patients and healthy trauma exposed controls (i.e., signiﬁcant
interaction between stimulus and group). In the ﬁrst time window,
brain regions in which a signiﬁcant interaction was found were in
two dlPFC clusters, one ranging between the left anterior part of
the middle frontal gyrus and the inferior frontal gyrus (F(1,28) =
15.288, p < .001) and another in the left posterior part of the mid-
dle frontal gyrus (F(1,28) = 13.686, p < .001), as well as clusters in
the right (F(1,28) = 13.002, p < .001) and left (F(1,28) = 12.043,
p < .01) parahippocampal gyrus and in the right (F(1,28) = 20.754,
p < .001) and left (F(1,28) = 20.290, p < .001) postcentral and pre-
central gyrus. In the second time window, a signiﬁcant interaction
was found only in the right middle frontal (orbital) gyrus (F(1,28)
= 10.634, p < .01) (Table 2). All clusters exceeded the threshold of
the permutation test (see Supplementary Methods in Supplemen-
tary Information).
Bonferroni-corrected post hoc comparisons on these interaction
effects revealed that in the ﬁrst time window, PTSD patients
showed increased activation in response to the target stimuli in
the left and right parahippocampal gyrus, whereas in the control
group parahippocampal activity was not enhanced in response to
target stimuli. The opposite pattern was evident in the left and
right postcentral/precentral gyrus in the ﬁrst time window, and
in the second time window in the right middle orbital frontal gyrus
(Fig. 2), with increased activation of the control group in response
to the target stimuli, but no such activity enhancement in the PTSD
group. Finally, in the ﬁrst time window, in the dlPFC clusters (left
anterior and left posterior middle frontal gyri) a disordinal interac-
tion was found, with higher activity of the PTSD relative to controls
in response to standard stimuli, but lower activity in response to
target stimuli (Fig. 3).
